    "XP pool formula fix (build 310). User: 'Looks like the formula needs help. a lot of % over 100%'. Build-309 grid had 11 runs with xp_pct > 100% because the per-M-tile estimate was a flat `(z+1)*8 + z*z*2` and ignored spawn-level offsets baked into game_systems.py spawn logic. Now reads each M tile's properties at snapshot time: tomb_elite -> floor+1 level (game_systems.py:2613), undead_guardian (non-elite) -> floor level, has_zots_guardian / is_boss_arena -> vault-defender XP (level+1)*100 (game_systems.py:727, 4x baseline). Spot check s=314 dwarf F5: 95/98 kills, xp_pct 97% (was 274% under the flat formula). Residual >100% cases would now come from non-tile XP (Carnyx kills, Experience Boost potions, library reads if any).",
    "Exploration efficiency metric (build 309). User: 'evaluate exp + treasure left on each level to see if better exploring would help with survival.' PlaytestSession.floor_totals[z] snapshots the floor's M / C / G / L / O / A / P / V / T / N / Q / K / B / F / X tile counts plus an expected xp_pool ((z+1)*8 + z*z*2 per M tile) on first arrival. playtest_report captures the snapshot per floor + the new xp_by_floor counter that sums kill-XP from log lines. summary_row exposes monsters_total / monsters_killed / kill_pct / xp_pool / xp_earned / xp_pct / chests_total / boons_total. Per-run page gains an Exploration section showing per-floor kills/M, XP/pool, chests, boons, vendor, tomb counts with overall totals. Index table gains an XP % column with the raw ratio. Smoke check on s=256 dwarf F6: 97/144 kills (67%) and 3218/4668 XP (69%) — clear signal that the agent is leaving real value on the floor.",
    "Cooking-kit polish (build 308). User: 'put the kit back on floor 3 vendor and have the player cook all their meat once they have the kit. Eating cooked meat is much better for survival.' Two changes: (1) Cooking Kit returns to F3+ vendor stock (was briefly F4+ in build 307; the original game tier was F3+ all along -- items.py:2499 comment 'Cooking Kit available from floor 3+'). Iron Rations stay at F1+. (2) Smart-policy cook-meat trigger drops the `hunger > 50` gate -- now fires whenever has_cooking_kit AND has_raw_meat exists. CookingKit.use() cooks ALL raw meat in one action, so this auto-converts the entire raw-meat backlog the moment the agent picks up the kit. urgent_meat (about-to-rot) still fires first because it's checked higher in the priority cascade. Earlier flatlines stay dead, s=13 elf still hits F9.",
    "Balance pass v2: kill the HP=1 starvation wedge, buff food economy. Build-305 grid found 3/60 agents pinned at HP=1 hunger=0 in game_loop indefinitely because `process_hunger` used max(1, hp-dmg) -- starvation couldn't actually kill, so doomed agents wandered forever. Three coordinated fixes: (1) `max(1, ...)` -> `max(0, ...)` at items.py:3175. Food clock can now run out; move_player's post-tick is_alive() check flips to death_screen on HP=0. New log: 'You collapse from starvation...'. Playtest report's _derive_death_cause recognises it. (2) Rations nutrition 40 -> 50 across vendor + drop sites + starter pack. Each ration goes further. (3) Starter pack rations 5 -> 8 (200 -> 400 nutrition cushion). (4) Smart-policy eat trigger 70 -> 50: rations now restore close-to-cap value at hunger=49 (50 of 51 used) instead of wasting 20 nutrition to the cap at hunger=69. Spot check 12 seeds: 3 prior flatlines (s=13 human, s=256 dwarf, s=1100 dwarf) now die honestly. Depth up: s=500 dwarf F3->F5, s=5678 dwarf F3->F6, s=314 dwarf F4->F6, s=7777 human F5->F6. Starvation now lethal but agents reach deeper before food runs out.",
    "Balance pass: tiered HP regen by hunger band (user: 'lets work on balance so some are still alive without looping at the end'). Existing regen fired only at hunger >= 85 (1 HP / 2 moves) -- a 15-move window after each meal. Past that the agent stopped recovering chip damage entirely, so wraith / poison / starvation ticks bled them to HP=1 on floors they could otherwise survive. Added a second tier in process_hunger (items.py:3149): when 60 <= hunger < 85, regen 1 HP / 4 moves (the 'sated cruise' band). hunger < 60: no regen, your meal is wearing off. Same gate is still gated on `health < max_health`. Starving agents (h <= 0) still TAKE damage so this never resurrects a doomed run. Smaller blast radius than buffing potion magnitudes or monster damage -- just smooths the chip-damage curve so honest survivors can maintain HP between fights through their full food window. Spot check 8 seeds: 2 flatlines from build 304 (s=256 dwarf F3 HP=1, s=1100 dwarf F2 HP=1) now die honestly instead.",
    "Build-303 flatline audit: die-fighting + spare-canister-aware lantern. Six survivors flatlined at HP=1 on F1-F4 with 90%+ waste_pct. Audit found two distinct trap shapes. (1) Arwen Silverleaf (s=42 elf F1) wedged at HP=1 with 2 spare lantern canisters, all immediate neighbours known, but a tomb-guardian M blocked her only exit east -- the periodic stuck-fire gate required `lantern_fuel > 5` (the in-lantern reservoir alone) so her 2 spare cans worth 40 fuel total never triggered the long-range reveal. Switched the gate to `fuel_total > 5` (lantern + spare * 10) so canister-rich agents still fire periodically. (2) Same Arwen scenario: starving (hunger=0) at HP=1, only path forward is through an M she's not strong enough to fight. is_weak's wayfinder tier strips M, so she paced two `.` tiles forever without ever stepping toward the only threat. Added trapped-engage-M override: when retreat_to_floor is None AND trapped_no_d AND no warp_path AND nearest_monster_path exists, priority becomes [('M',)] and the M tier bypasses _swap_if_backtrack (same shape as the W tier) so the agent commits to the engage instead of bouncing. Combat-mode flee gates already skip when starving so she fights to the end -- 'die fighting' beats the indefinite HP=1 flatline. Spot check 9 seeds: Arwen now reaches F4 dead (was F1 alive at T3000), s=42 human F3 dead (was F2 alive), s=314 dwarf dies honestly, two flatlines remain (s=256 elf F4, s=271 elf F8 -- different trap shapes, not the die-fighting class).",
    "Inferred-guardian-tile detection (no nerfs, just smarter playtester). User: 'before we nerf anything, lets see if we can create playtests logic that detects \"a tomb might be here so there could be a guardian in one of these adjacent rooms.\"' Two new obs fields: (1) suspected_guardian_coords -- set of (x,y) tiles cardinal-adjacent to ANY discovered T on the current floor. Every tomb spawns exactly four cardinal guardians (dungeon.py:545 setup_dungeons_and_tombs), so once the agent SEES the T they can infer the four corner positions without having to discover the M tiles directly. (2) inferred_guardian_dirs -- the cardinal directions whose adjacent tile sits in suspected_guardian_coords. Folded into the same blocked_guardian_dirs release-gate as the M-confirmed tomb_guardian_dirs (`pc.level >= pc.floor + 3` to engage). Also added to _walkable() in the random fallback so the cornered random walk doesn't blunder in either. Spot-check 33 seeds: s=271 elf reaches F8 (new project depth, was F7), 6 alive runs (was 0 in build 302), elf seed 7 escapes F1 (was killed by ELITE UNDEAD LICHEN at T<200). No nerf to spawn / stats / release-threshold -- the agent just has better domain knowledge.",
    "ELITE UNDEAD LICHEN was a thing: game-side undead-template filter had the same substring bug as the harness. Audit of the build-301 grid showed 100% of elite-undead deaths (15/15) came from the cardinal-adjacent guardian M tiles (the four corners around every T tile), 0 from tomb raids. The 'ELITE UNDEAD LICHEN' name surfaced because game_systems.py:2622 picked the Lichen template via `any(t in m['name'] for t in undead_types)` -- 'Lich' substring matched 'Lichen'. Fixed with the same word-boundary regex shape as the harness fix. Also two report normalizations: (1) `_normalize_monster_name` helper strips leading 'the ' + collapses internal whitespace, so 'The  ELITE UNDEAD WRAITH' (the combat log's 'The X strikes first!' on a leading-space monster name) canonicalizes to 'ELITE UNDEAD WRAITH'. The death-cause histogram no longer splits the same monster into multiple buckets. (2) Applied in both the path-1 `you were defeated by...` regex and the path-4 fallback's _extract_recent_attacker.",
